article.description: Ticha Penicheiro lifted the Monarchs to a 60-50 victory over the Lynx that snapped a three-game skid Thursday night.
article.headline: Sac PG becomes all-time assist leader
article.linkText: PG Penicheiro shines as Monarchs beat Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Ticha Penicheiro filled the stat sheet in
helping Sacramento snap a three-game slide.

Penicheiro had 10 points and seven assists Thursday night and
made a key 3-pointer down the stretch to lift the Monarchs to a
60-50 victory over the Minnesota Lynx.

"It's a relief to get a win, period," Penicheiro said. "Right
now, I feel like we won a championship."

Hamchetou Maiga tied a career high with 12 points, and Yolanda
Griffith had 13 points and eight rebounds for the Monarchs, who
scored 25 points off turnovers.

"We relied on our defense because our offense is not working,"
Griffith said after her team, ranked near the bottom of the league
offensively, shot just 33.3 percent from the field.

Griffith and Tangela Smith had five steals each and the Monarchs
had five players score in double figures.

Katie Smith had 16 points and Nicole Ohlde added 13 for the
Lynx, who committed a season-high 25 turnovers and shot even worse
than Sacramento at 32.6 percent.

"They capitalized on our mistakes and just took it away from
us," Smith said. "These are things that we control, which is why
it is so disappointing.

"But give them credit, they played very, very hard."

Smith's 3-pointer with 3:48 remaining gave Minnesota its only
lead of the second half, 47-46. But Sacramento responded with an
8-0 run, sparked by Penicheiro's 3-pointer with one minute left.

The Monarchs came out strong in the second half to take a 35-28
lead at the 14-minute mark. But the Lynx came back with seven
unanswered points, capped by Tamika Williams' only field goal to
tie it 35-35 with 10:20 left.

The teams played evenly the rest of the way before the Monarchs
made their final push.

Sacramento got out to an 8-2 lead and extended to an 11-4
advantage as Minnesota struggled from the field. The Lynx missed
nine of their first 10 shots.

Smith made consecutive 3-pointers and Amanda Lassiter hit a shot
with 8:20 left to give Minnesota its first lead, 12-11. Sacramento
was scoreless for more than six minutes before Griffith gave the
Monarchs the lead back.

Lassiter came back with a 3-pointer, but Sacramento closed the
half on a 12-6 run led by Maiga's 10 points to take a 25-21 lead
into the break.

Penicheiro's assist to Maiga with 5.8 seconds remaining in the
first half gave Sacramento's point guard 1,317 assists for her
career, passing Teresa Weatherspoon for the WNBA's career lead.
Weatherspoon currently plays for Los Angeles.

"It's not like she is retired," Penicheiro said when asked
about her accomplishment. "Right now, I'm just happy we won,"

Penicheiro and Weatherspoon are the only players with more than
1,000 assists.
